# AWS Deployment Rules

## Credentials
- NEVER commit AWS credentials, `.tfvars` with secrets, or `.env` files with keys
- EC2 uses IAM instance profiles — no static keys in container env vars
- Lambda uses an execution role with least-privilege S3 read-only
- GitHub Actions uses OIDC — no static keys in CI

## Deployment workflow
- Run `make test-web` locally before any deploy
- Use `make deploy` for full pipeline (build → push → infra → verify)
- Use `make deploy-infra` for infrastructure-only changes
- Use `make deploy-ec2` for container-only updates (no infra change)
- Use `make deploy-lambda` for Lambda code updates
- Use `make deploy-static` for frontend-only updates (JS, CSS, static JSON)
- NEVER make Console changes — all infra through Terraform

## Post-deploy
- Always run `make verify-aws` (or `make test-deploy`) after deployment
- Check `make audit-aws` periodically to ensure no resource drift

## Infrastructure
- All resources in `infra/` Terraform configs
- Tag everything: `Project=danger-finger`, `Environment={dev|prod}`, `ManagedBy=terraform`
- ECR lifecycle keeps last 10 images
- Terraform state in S3 with DynamoDB locking

## Cost awareness
- EC2 t3a.medium is the default (~$27/mo)
- Consider scheduling stop/start for dev if not used 24/7
- Run `make audit-aws` to check for unexpected cost increases
